For the Metro Issue what was happening was,When the cron runs, it will do a targetCompletionStatus API call in a paginated manner i.e fetch 1000 records at a time until all the records are fetched sequentially. Due to high volume of records for Metro, the call was timing out sometimes. For Example, lets assume that there are 1 lakh records for Metro org.  The 1st API call with fetch records from 1- 1000, then the 2nd API call will fetch 1001 - 2000, then the 3rd will fetch from 2001 - 3000 and so on until all records are successfully fetched.Because of high number of records, the API performance is a little degraded, which means it take lot of time to send the response. Sometimes it takes 8 seconds , sometimes 15 seconds. Due to this the calls which responded < 10 seconds were picked up by the cron and the one which timed out due to readTimeOut default value being 10 seconds, all the records after the timeout did also not get picked.12:00 --- Cron Runs --- Fetches 1-1000, 1001 - 2000 and times out during the 2001 - 3000 call.1:00 --- Cron runs again --- Fetches 3001 - 4000 and times out during 4001 - 5000 record2:00 Cron runs ---- Fetches 5001 - 6000 and so onThis process kept on repeating and the number of records got divided at every hour.As a quick fix we decreased the cron time to 10 mins for faster evaluation of pending records.This ticket was to increase the timeout until we either optimise the APi properly or figure out something else.The change from increasing the readTimeout from 10 seconds to 2 minutes was done and has been released alreadycc @Akhilesh Baldi @Raginee Kumari @Bhuvaneshwari Seshachalam", "mentions": []}]

